    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>With Nader In, G.O.P. Dreams May Come True</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sidney Wertimer letter says Ralph Nader's candidacy could swing election in favor of Republicans (July 4 letter)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Let us grant Ralph Nader his position that the two major parties are lookalikes and that he has something different to offer (letter, July 4). Do the voters want his offering?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Let us grant Ralph Nader his position that the two major parties are lookalikes and that he has something different to offer (letter, July 4). Do the voters want his offering?</p>
        <p>Some, no doubt, do -- say, 5 percent. The probable effect will be to take Electoral College votes away from the Democrats and add them to the Republicans, possibly swinging the election. One result would be  conservative Supreme Court nominations. Is this real possibility a part of Mr. Nader's noble intention?</p>
        <p>SIDNEY WERTIMER  Clinton, N.Y., July 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
